properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls expected overnight into Sunday. Snow squalls are expected to develop overnight as a low pressure system departs from Southern Ontario. Snow squalls are expected to continue for much of the day Sunday before moving south of the area while weakening. Northwest winds gusting 60 or 70 km/h will also result in widespread blowing snow along with these snow squalls. Total snowfall amounts up to 20 cm are possible from these snow squalls by Sunday evening. The highest amounts are expected along the Lake Huron shoreline from Kincardine and south towards Grand Bend. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: A significant snowfall continues. An additional few centimetres of snow are possible early this evening. This is forecast to bring total snowfall accumulations up to 15 cm over some areas. The snow will continue to taper to flurries this evening. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A strong Pacific storm has arrived with a mix of wintery weather including snow and freezing rain for the eastern and central Fraser Valley. As warmer air associated with the storm penetrates the region, the snow will transition to freezing rain then to rain tonight. Total snowfall accumulations of 5 to 10 cm is expected.. Timing this transition from snow to freezing rain is always challenging in these situations. There is a chance that this transition could be delayed resulting in higher snowfall amounts. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-19T15:30:15-00:00

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. Light snow and strong northwest winds continue to affect portions of the Red River valley. Reduced visibilities in drifting or blowing snow continues to occurring in open areas where visibilities are at times reduced to less than 400 metres. Conditions are expected to improve throughout the night as winds diminish. Anyone who needs to travel on area highways tonight should ensure that they check local weather forecasts: (https://weather.gc.ca/forecast/canada/index_e.html?id=mb) and regional highway conditions: (https://manitoba511.ca/en/) before travelling. Ensure that your vehicle contains a winter emergency kit: (https://www.getprepared.gc.ca/cnt/rsrcs/sfttps/tp201012-en.aspx). Travel conditions have also deteriorated through the Dakotas and Minnesota, where this disturbance has also brought snow and strong winds. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with amounts near 20 cm expected today. Snow, at times heavy will continue this evening, with total amounts of 15 to 20 cm expected. Southeasterly winds gusting to 50 km/h will whip up the freshly fallen snow causing low visibilities at times in blowing snow this evening. Additionally, cold arctic air is expected to make a return to the region tonight allowing lake effect snow to develop and persist through Sunday. The lake effect snow is expected to provide additional snowfall accumulations to some communities tonight and through Sunday. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Light to moderate northwesterly winds combined with temperatures in the minus thirties will produce windchill values of -40 or lower tonight. Windchill values will moderate during the day on Sunday, however they may return to warning-levels over southeastern Saskatchewan Sunday night into Monday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
